                    "heading": {
                        "type": "heading",
                        "content": "elecricity and safety",
                        "level": 2
                    },
                    "items": [
                        {
                            "type": "image",
                            "src": "https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/userfiles/c/c057f0fe9554fc3e8c108ff70dbf125fa29a2e70.JPG",
                            "altText": "Safety first",
                            "alignment": "right",
                            "scale": 0.3,
                            "link": ""
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "paragraph",
                            "content": "<p>Go to: <a href=\"https://www.ccohs.ca/oshanswers/safety_haz/electrical.html\">https://www.ccohs.ca/oshanswers/safety_haz/electrical.html</a></p>\n<p>Answer the following questions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong><em>How many people are killed in the Netherlands because of electrical accidents?Look for these data on the internet.</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>What happens if people are severely electrocuted.?</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>Explain the difference between 'static'and 'dynamic' electricity.</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>Static electricity is based on 'accumulation of charge'. The word 'deficiency' is used. Write down in English how this works.</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>Describe three kinds of injuries when being electrocuted.</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>Why do people have to stay in their car when coming close to broken powerlines?</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>What is the danger when using the wrong type of fuse?</em></strong></li>\n<li><strong><em>What to do when working in hot or damp environments? Explain this.</em></strong></li>\n</ol>\n"
                        }
                    ],
                    "sections": []
